	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Proposed changes to all priest classes</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><b>Core Healing Spells</b> <br />
All priests share as common/core healing spells the "heal/remedy" line of spells, starting with minor healing at level 1, ending with supernal remedy in PoP.  The lower level versions do not change, but starting at 39, when clerics get complete heal, druids and shamans get their versions 5 levels later.  Each classes' hybrid receives the same spells (excluding cheal which is now changed to be a "priest" specialty) +8 levels later (level 9 for minor healing, instead of level 1, and so on)<br />
<br />
<i>Change to Complete Heal</i> <br />
At the level first gained, it heals 2560hp, every level thereafter, it improves by 240pts, resulting in clerics having a 10k heal at level 70, and druids/shamans having an 8.8k heal at level 70.  Innate cleric healing power starts out close to 1.5x as powerful in direct heals when druids/shamans first get complete heal, but then drops steadily over time until at level 70 its around 1.16 times more powerful.  At each level, a cleric will heal for 240*5=1200pts more than the other priests. represenatative of the equivilent of innate warrior tanking being *slightly* better.<br />
<br />
<i>Resurrections</i> <br />
All existing cleric resurrection spells, ending at "resurrection" at level 49, are defined to be "priest spells", with druids/shamans getting them 5 levels later than their cleric counterparts, thus getting a 90% rez at level 54.  Paladins changed to get resurrection as a level 57 spell (retaining the +8 level progression) and also getting reviviscence at level 63.<br />
<br />
<i>Buffs</i><br />
All priest buffs are changed to to be reagentless, and the cleric symbol line is dropped in light of the expanded aegolism line.  All priests get group versions of their buffs 1 circle later than their single-target versions.  Furthermore, all priest spells are 100% stackable, but effects that are identical are non-cumulative but rather "the best of each" is taken.  Buff 1 has better AC and buff 2 has better HP, a peson with both buffs up gets the benefits of the AC from buff 1, and the HP from buff 2.<br />
<br />
<i>Summary</i><br />
Stacking issues of buffs resolved once and for all.  All priests now have a choice between "fast inefficient" and "slow efficient" healing spells that scale with level based on when first aquired.  No longer will a level 39 cleric have a better single-target heal than a druid regardless of level.  All priests can rez, although between having a higher percentage rez and the kunark epic click rez, clerics are slightly better in this area as well.  Bottom line: a group can take a druid or a shaman as main healer and expect them to have the minimum tools needed to get the job done.<br />
<br />
<b>Cleric Healing Specializations</b> <br />
<i>The Light Line</i> <br />
The Light line of spells represents a mid-point in direct heals between the power of complete heal, and the speed of the faster heals.  Clerics as "direct healing specialists" keep this line of spells exclusive to themselves.<br />
<br />
<i>The Elixers (HoTs)</i> <br />
Clerics and Druids would get all heal over time spells at the same levels, clerics by virtue of being healing specialists, druids by virtue of being already talented in heal-over-time spells as present in their regeneration-line spells.  Shamans have their own unique heal over time spells, and these would be instead back-scaled through levels and uptuned in power through focus items and gear for the high end.<br />
<br />
<i>Innate healing crits instead of healing bonus</i> <br />
Instead of a flat +X% to healing power, substituted by having clerics get the spells sooner, clerics instead get an innate chance to land exceptional heals identically to how wizards innate can land critical blasts.<br />
<br />
<b>Druid Healing Specialities</b> <br />
<i>Healing over Time</i> <br />
In addition to sharing the existing cleric heal-over-time spells, druids would get their own "mid-range" HoTs that form a mid-point between the supreme long-term efficiency of regeneration spells, and the short-term "fix them quickly" elixers shared with clerics.  <br />
<br />
<i>Innate Bonus to HP/tick on HoTs</i><br />
Just as clerics get an innate chance to score exceptional heals, the druidic equivilent would seemingly be the equivilent of "burning affliction" for dots, although this would simply be likely far to "spammy" for most people.  Instead druid-cast HoTs would be 5-10% more powerful in hp/tick healed than cleric equivilents.<br />
<br />
<b>Shaman Healing Specialization</b><br />
<i>Torpor</i><br />
This spell would be scaled back in levels and vendor buyable, with torpor remaining a drop/researched spell and its upgrade quiesence remaining a parchment turn in.  A potent single-target heal-over-time with the disadvantage of a snare effect to balance it, provides the shaman class with a class-unique form of the HoT that is situationally better than the druidic version, but generally slightly weaker.<br />
<br />
<i>Debuffs</i><br />
The shaman debuff line would be moved from being a core ability of the class to a secondary (though certainly prominent) one.  Slow is widely shared in effective levels in other classes, particularly in the high end where slow-mitigating mobs have made it all-but pointless according to shaman posters to even try and cast it.<br />
<br />
<i>Spirit of Healing</i><br />
In keeping with shamans as allies of the spirits, they get the ability to summon a "healing spirit" that follows them like a wizard's familiar (only without the annoying flapping sound) and only functions when present, and is targettable, but has very high AC, HP, and excellent natural regen that makes killing it a real challenge for enemies.  This "healing spirit" acts in two ways. First everyone in range of it within the shaman's group or raid recieves a slight boost to innate mitigation (ranging from .5% to 5% at highest level).  Secondly, it provides an ongoing form of steady hp regeneration ala bardsong, with its effect being represented in the bard-box.  Range is short, and unaffected by focus effects, being perhaps radial range of 50 from point of healing spirit.  Like any other pet, the healing spirit is non-aggro to mobs, and its healing/buffing effects non-aggro except where they work on PCs already on a mobs hate list.  Group restriction is both a tool to prevent it benefitting enemies in PvP and from being used as a PLing tool.<br />
<br />
(part 2, non-healing)</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
