			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Learning the ways</div>
			
		
			
				<div class="smallfont">
					&nbsp;<br /><a href="member.php?s=2fb873c7ce6cc00a3b888667a4cd61b9&amp;u=2294"><img src="images/avatars/cleric005.gif" alt="katahn's Avatar" border="0" /></a>
				</div>
			
			
			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>Join Date: Feb 2004</div>
				<!--
				 -->

				<div>
					Posts: 96
				</div>
				
				<div>   <a href="#" onclick="return imwindow('yahoo', '2294', 400, 200)"><img src="images/tdg/misc/im_yahoo.gif" alt="Send a message via Yahoo to katahn" border="0" /></a></div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Proposed Changes, part 2, non-healing aspects (clerics and druids)</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><b>Things that remain unchanged</b> <br />
Druids and shamans retain their speed buffs as in modern EQ, these have become group conveniences rather than selling points in an age of boosted runspeed.<br />
<br />
Druids retain their existing teleportation and evac spells as again, in an age of rapid travel via PoK, the Nexus, and LDoN Magi, rapid teleportation of groups is considerably less useful as a "raw ability" or "group friendly feature" than it once used to be.  They also retain their existing snare spells.<br />
<br />
Both druids and shamans should generally be considered to retain any existing utility not mentioned below.  I do not confess to be an expert in either class and will not pretend to know all about them.<br />
<br />
<b>Cleric Changes</b> <br />
<i>Manaless DPS</i> <br />
The original intent of the hammers and YaulpV was to give clerics a "meaningful source of mana-free damage based in a spell so its overall DPS could be more easily adjusted."  This turned out to be a major problem as melee DPS classes, and even tank classes, complained about cleric melee bitterly, the resultant nerf on the hammers is now a matter of historical fact.  In keeping with the spirit in which this was intended, and in honest reflection of the fact that a cleric casting 1 nuke per fight averages better DPS, change the summoned proccing hammers to be a permanent and commandable pet, power-balanced in its base values against the shaman pet, and having a lower innate natural proc of "Hnd of the Gods".<br />
<br />
Backscaled through the levels, this pet provides clerics with a decent source of constant DPS even when needing to be a healer, diminishing as pet-level weakens relative to mob level, and being weaker than a magician or beastlord pet, is certainly not going to represent a massive soloing boost for clerics, even combined with an innate proc.  Furthermore, since its a hammer, and hammers have no logical consistency in wearing armor or wielding weapons, the hammer pet would have no inventory slots associated with it, and instead would be wholly reliant on being buffed and maintained by its owner.<br />
<br />
<i>Nukes</i> <br />
Drop all the specialized anti-undead nukes currently held by clerics.  Reduce casting times by a factor of 1/2, eliminate pushback on all nuking spells while leaving it on stuns, change the base damage to be of the same "type" as the hand of the gods proc (unresistable, but always random) using the existing cleric general "nukes" for maximum damage they can do unfocused.  <br />
<br />
Next add two anti-undead features to these nukes.  The first being an innate chance to score a critical blast when nuking undead.  The second being an innate damage bonus when nuking the undead.  These should combine so that level-for-level, a cleric nuking undead can match the general-purpose nukes of a wizard.  The limited number of undead mobs, and the thematic appropriateness of clerics being a real threat to undead, both justify this and lay to rest concerns of clerics suddenly being seen as a "viable DPS class" or remotely competitive to them.<br />
<br />
Third, return the "Turn Undead" AA to act like the paladin "Slay Undead" when used by clerics nuking undead.  It increases the chance of scoring a "cleansing blast" which further increases the damage a cleric can do to the undead.  This fixes an AA the cleric community widely regards as horribly broken, and firmly establishes clerics as "destroyers of the undead."<br />
<br />
<i>Crowd Control</i> <br />
When the pacification line was first denerfed, the cleric class experienced a brief surge of "fun" as clerics could more effectively play "poor man's enchanter" through its use.  Its renerfing later in relation to its mana cost, made the spell effectively useless in the opinion of many, if not a majority, of clerics.  Restoring the duration of pacification, and reducing the chance of getting aggro from it to half its current chance, would allow a cleric to act as a puller in groups where another priest is healing, or if called on to do so, would be hard-pressed to have mana to do anything but.<br />
<br />
Secondly, with root-immune mobs in some zones as a over-the-top response to stop kiters, and with mobs that cast spells or have other ranged attacks, a role of "poor man's crowd control" via use of the root spell is one that has fallen by the wayside.  Introducing a new series of cleric "mez" spells that are called instead "hold" spells could let them duplicate this former technique, and especially in confined dungeons where root-parking adds isn't always possible.  Hold spells would have a maximum of 2/3 the duration of equivilent enchanter mezzes, and cost 150% as much mana, and would be broken as soon as said mob took damage of any kind just as a normal mez.<br />
<br />
<i>Summary of Cleric Secondary Abilities</i> <br />
1. Manafree damage shifted from hammer to persistent pet.  Low base damage, occasional procs, and even buffed generally too low in hp/ac to be able to tank, lacking any inventory slots it would not be enhanceable with summoned pet items , and being a hammer would get double attack instead of dual wield and double attack.<br />
<br />
2. Nukes changed to variable damage, unresistable "Hand of the Gods" nukes with max normal damage being as present.  This resolves the need to expand clerics by giving them more nukes, and the randomness of the damage is its own counterbalance to not being resist-dependant.  Damage versus undead would be increased, along with innate crits, balanced against a scarcity of undead mobs and included for thematic appropriateness.<br />
<br />
3. Cleric CC abilities restored and tuned to be genuinely less effective than what enchanters can do, but in the absence of an echanter, and with another priest to heal, it is a real group role a cleric could fill and one that is generally underrepresented (only 2 classes have universal CC outside of this, bards and enchanters, both have group desirability that extends beyond this limited function, which they would still be better at.)<br />
<br />
<b>Druids</b> <br />
Druids already have a wide variety of secondary abilities, although complaints of the increasing uselessness of some of them from a group-friendly perspective certainly bear being considered.<br />
<br />
<i>Mana Free DPS</i><br />
Rather than give druids pets, or even have them summon, charm, or dire charm animals (situationally useful at best I have heard the claim made) perhaps we might look at druid wolf and tree forms and make them useful.<br />
<br />
Common Features of being shapechanged:<br />
* Sylvan creatures base faction outside of class/diety starts out at amiable.<br />
* Either form is only innately KOS in places where either a wolf or treant would be KOS if it weren't a shapeshifted druid.  <br />
* Spell gems are greyed out while in an alternate form, preventing spellcasting.<br />
* Shapeshifted forms are "noclip" to player characters so a fighting druid in these forms does not present an obstacle to other pure DPS classes.<br />
<br />
Wolf Form (Self-only version)<br />
* Progressive (throughout the series) increase to attack score<br />
* Progressive innate increase in haste, stackable but not cumulative with other spell based haste.<br />
* Progressive increase in +damage bonus<br />
* Innate runspeed improvement<br />
* Track range increased progressively through levels, and tracking is defaulted to "tracksort by distance" and cannot be changed while in this form.<br />
* Indifferant to all animal mobs with rare exceptions (animals trained by masters for war would be exempt for instance, such as the wolves of the kael drakkel giants)<br />
<br />
Intent: Wolf Form becomes a "offensive melee" form for druids, enabling them to contribute meaningful DPS in groups outside of nuking or using mana otherwise being able to cast at all.  Defensively nothing changes, so this form cannot reliably be used to tank at all.<br />
<br />
Tree (Treant) Form<br />
* Self-only Regenerating Rune, regenerating 10% per tick, progressively scaling up through levels.<br />
* Self-only HP buff (stacks with other HP buffs), progressively scaling up through levels.<br />
* Self-only AC buff (stacks with other AC buffs), progressively scaling up through levels.<br />
* No change in attack or combat skills, but each attack (hit or miss) generates hate in an amount that progresses as above.  Justification: while not huge damage, lots of flailing branches and blowing leaves certainly represents a lot of taunting factor.<br />
* In treant form the druid's movement rate is reduced by 50% and cannot be enhanced by spell or AA.<br />
* In treant form the druid's fire resist is reduced to 0, although effects of buffs still work, worn equipment would not, as one does not typically see walking trees running around in armor.  Lowered FR is explained simply as this: the druid is now made of wood.... <img src="http://thedruidsgrove.org/forums/images/smilies/wink.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Wink" class="inlineimg" /><br />
* As a group friendly feature, a druid in this form progressively enhances the passive hp/mana regeneration of their group mates.  If represented as a buff effect, it should go in the short duration box, and would have a radial range of 25 in all directions.<br />
<br />
<i>Nukes and Dots</i><br />
All existing druidc dot-lines would be dropped, instead druids would have a wider assortment of direct damage spells to choose from, corresonding to the "natural" elements: <br />
<br />
Storms/Lightning: Magic<br />
Animals: Poison<br />
Blizzard: Cold<br />
Summer's Wrath: Fire<br />
Earthquake: PBAOE and stun (Magic)<br />
<br />
Each of these spell lines would be benchmarked against wizard spells, and designed with identical casting time, and mana costs, but with base damage set to 70% of a wizard's damage.  However, just as clerics are enemies of the undead, druids are enemies of the "unnatural" summoned or "construct" type creatures and would get the same damage bonus versus these types that clerics get versus undead.  <br />
<br />
<i>Crowd Control, and the Indoor Restrictions</i><br />
Druidic harmony spells should get the same tender loving care due to the cleric pacification line, and then should be made useful regardless of being inside or out.  Even if druids are the only class to get this benefit of their spells (sow, harmony, etc.) working in all environments, it makes sense thematically as nature can be felt everywhere, and the "masters of nature" should not be so arbitrarily limited.<br />
<br />
(part 3 coming)</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
