			<div class="smallfont">Learning the ways</div>
			
		
			
				<div class="smallfont">
					&nbsp;<br /><a href="member.php?s=2fb873c7ce6cc00a3b888667a4cd61b9&amp;u=2294"><img src="images/avatars/cleric005.gif" alt="katahn's Avatar" border="0" /></a>
				</div>
			
			
			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>Join Date: Feb 2004</div>
				<!--
				 -->

				<div>
					Posts: 96
				</div>
				
				<div>   <a href="#" onclick="return imwindow('yahoo', '2294', 400, 200)"><img src="images/tdg/misc/im_yahoo.gif" alt="Send a message via Yahoo to katahn" border="0" /></a></div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Part Three (shaman non-healing changes)</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><b>Shamans</b><br />
<i>Nukes and Dots</i><br />
Where druids lose their dots, shamans lose their nukes.  Instead shamanic dots retain their existing damage dealing power at full effect, but have the delivery time reduced to 1/3 current durations.  Where a dot would take 3 minutes to fully work, it would now take 1 minute, while over that one minute doing the same damage.  This provides shaman DPS with a distinctly differant feel than either druid or cleric DPS.<br />
<br />
<i>Pet</i><br />
As the original priest pet class, shamans are fully entitled to expect that pet to not only stay around, but be useful as a source of manafree damage.  To that end, shaman pets are as equippable as any pet today is, shamans being added to the list of classes capable of casting existing beastlord "pet proc buffs", and the pet coming innately hasted as if so done by the best haste spell available at the level the pet spell was summoned at.  The pet would dual-wield (it does have two paws) automatically, gaining opportunities do eventually double and even triple attack as normal.  In relationship to the cleric hammer, this pet's melee damage would be greater, capable of using equipment, although not automatically any more capable of tanking than the hammer.<br />
<br />
<i>The Spirits</i><br />
The Spirits are the allies of the shaman, aiding their allies, and striking down their enemies.  Shamans have the option of summoning special spirit allies (limit of one) in addition to their existing pet.  These are, in essence, shamanic familiars.<br />
<br />
Spirit of Life: Already mentioned in healing<br />
Spirit of Battle: Allies in group and in range get a stackable +attack and +damage bonus.<br />
Spirit of Death: Enemies in range are weakened and slowed slightly, an unresistable effect but one overwritten by regular slow/cripple spells.<br />
Spirit of Fire: Enhances the damage done by all fire based effects of allies in range.<br />
Spirit of (other elements): see Spirit of Fire<br />
Spirit of the Land: The shaman and their allies in range are automatically hidden from the sight of not only the living, but the unliving as well, as this spirit guards them on both levels.<br />
Spirit of Magic: Much like spirit of life, except more quickly restoring mana to the allies of the shaman in range and in group.<br />
<br />
and so on.  The summoned spirits in some cases would need to retain either short fixed durations or random durations, as appropriate to the spells they model.  Buff-type effects they give go to the short duration buff window, and all negative effects to enemies are set to be unresistable and automatic if in range, but at a suitably low level so that any active cast of the "real spell" would overtake and thus take predominance.<br />
<br />
<i>Cannibalization</i><br />
This spell would change from being "active hp-for-mana regeneration" to being pasive like the comparable line of spells held by necromancers.  Scaled through levels, and subject to the same limitations, a shaman takes on a "spirit" or semi-transparent image where the necromancer appears skeletal, and appears as a floating wisp of visible "spirit energy" where the necromancer looks like a spectre.  Where a necromancer using their spell can use a mount, the shaman equivilent could as well, and where they could not, neither could the shaman.  Futhermore, this spell would not stack with the clarity line of enchanters, although it would stack with druidic and beastlord buffs with mana regeneration components.<br />
<br />
<i>Shaman Summary</i><br />
Dots changed from "slow cook" to "deep fry" for better DPS<br />
Pet improvements made to add to effectiveness of doggy<br />
Canni changed to be more practical and useful in a game where movement has shifted from "sit and camp" to "move around a lot" and reflects that as cool as cannibalize is now, its simply impractical to shamans in more recent expansions.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
