	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				This strikes me as a very odd proposal.  You give shamans CHeals, which they never especially asked for, while removing their primary form of healing (that being the most efficient HoT spells in the game).  They also get Rez, which while nice has rarely been at the top of shaman wishlists.  At the same time, rather than improving the one line of spells shamans have been asking to have improved, the "mending" line (shaman version of "light" line), you basically claim it as the exclusive dominion of clerics.  And you give some sort of new pet to shamans that looks to be very similar to the AA "ward" ability that all three priests already have.  Another thing that shamans didn't especially ask for and which many are currently asking for refunds to from having spent AA points on it.  No shaman in his right mind would consider these changes even remotely reasonable unless I've misunderstood the specific proposal.<br />
<br />
Druids gain improved CHeal spells, a whole new line of very powerful HoT spells which they never had in the past, and rezzes.  They lose their "infusion" line since the "light" line has been reserved for clerics.  This would probably be a very fair exchange for druids.  But not having any fast direct heals would probably make healing in challenging content very difficult.  I'd guess druids overall would like this proposal, but I'm not sure about it, since not having fast direct heals is problematic.<br />
<br />
I'm not sure what clerics get out of this at all.  I presume their major changes will be in the non-healing part.<br />
<br />
In any case, to sum up:<br />
<br />
- transfering essentially the entire line of shaman HoT upgrades to druids is going to need A TON of justification to be even under consideration since it makes little to no sense.<br />
<br />
- leaving druids and shamans without their versions of the "light" line makes them entirely non-viable as healers in challenging content where cheal spells are too slow.<br />
<br />
- this proposal appears to bite for shamans and would cause even more of them to quit the game than is already happening
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
<br />
Speaking as a cleric, the light line comes into being for clerics in the 50s, and it isn't widely regarded as a good/useful line in relation to the heal/remedy line, or the elixer line, until the cleric has both HA3/HG3 and a nice spell haste IV item and spell haste buff.  Prior to that it always struck me as better as a non-raiding cleric to use either a HoT, a fast heal, or cheal for 99% of situations.<br />
<br />
Since the intent here is to balance grouping, this seemed fine.  As for druids getting HoT spells at the same time clerics get them, it seemed thematically appropriate given their superior regeneration line already, and to be honest, the lower level versions aren't that great efficiency-wise compared to their direct counterparts, being primarily lower aggro as the benefit.  At higher levels, in groups, HoTs were most often useful as something to drop on an incoming puller, or throw on a tank at the start of a fight, to buy the slower (and me) time to get the mob slowed, or adds locked down.  Since all three priests have HoTs for this purpose after this proposal, and druids are the only ones really lacking prior, I viewed it as basic fairness.<br />
<br />
Lastly, just because I don't mention explicitly keeping any given ability, does not mean I am removing it in this proposal, its fixes, and adjustments, not nerfs.  Besides, you commented on a post labeled part 1, with a note to part 2 coming, its not suprising some things seemed a bit odd.</div>
